## While it takes thousands of years for [[Unsorted/Soil\|Soil]] to be made naturally, we can facilitate the same effects with 5-10 years of composting


- "Compost" meaning:
	- Latin: "To put together"
- The correct amounts of compostable materials make great soil amendments
 - Compost is a stable material, dark brown or black, smells earthy due to Actinomycetes
 - Great source of microbes, micronutrients, and KP
	 - Has lost most of its nitrogen though


## How to compost

### How is compost created?
- Mixing high-nitrogen organic waste with high-carbon materials
	- Needs an appropriate ratio
		- 25-30:1 C:N
			- If too much carbon, decomposition slows down
			- If too low, becomes [[Unsorted/Respiration#Respiration Anaerobic\|Anaerobic]] and stinks
		- Ratios of common items
			- ~ Equal volume of greens and browns
			- ![Pasted image 20220926140026.png](data:image/png;base64,)
			- ![Pasted image 20220926140035.png](data:image/png;base64,)
			- 
		- But it doesn't need to be precise to be successful
	- Accelerates the breakdown of organic materials
	- Ideal size: 3x3x3 feet
	- Keep damp, but not wet
	- Gives it time to stabilize, mature, and cure
	- Turn compost every 2 weeks, encourage aerobic bacteria
- Natural composting is responsible for all [[Unsorted/Soil\|Soil]] on earth
- Microbes that are involved:
	- Initially by mesophilic organisms
		- Break down easily-degradable compounds
		- Increases temperature drastically, dies from the heat
	- Thermophilic organisms
		- A mixed [[Unsorted/Communities\|Community]] of Gram-positive bacteria and [[Unsorted/Fungi\|Mycorrhizal Fungi]]
		- [[Unsorted/Humans\|Human]] pathogens are destroyed at temps above 55°C
		- Accelerates the breakdown of complex carbohydrates like cellulose
	- Curing
		- Temperature decreases
		- Mesophilic bacteria take over again
		- Known as Humus
			- Compost that can't be broken down any further
			- When sold, kind of a scam
				- Can't be produced in a garden environment
				- Alleged organic matter that will not break down ; permanent


### Cold composting
- Passive: Layering materials and ignoring them
	- Weed seeds survive
	- Pathogenic [[Unsorted/Fungi\|Fungi]] and bacteria survive
	- Great for worms
	- Attracts rodents, good habitat

### Hot composting
- Active: Involves high temperatures
	- Destroys pathogens and weed seeds
	- Bacteria produce all the heat

### Benefits of compost
- Reduce/eliminane need for chemical fertilizers
- Higher crop yields
- Fascilitate reforestation, ecosystem restoration
- Remediate contaminated soil
	- Lead near freeways, arsenic in industrial areas
- Remove hazardous materials from runoff
	- Solids, oil, grease, heavy metals
- Increase [[Unsorted/Soil microbiology\|microbiological]] activity
- Inhibit soilborne diseases



### Things that can be composted
- ***Finer it's chopped, faster it breaks down***
- Almost all leaves
- Poison oak
- Sumac
- Shredded pine needles
- Shred magnolia leaves
- Kitchen waste
	- ***Avg kitchen produces 200lbs of waste yearly***
	- Fruit core and peels
	- Vegetable peelings
	- Old vegetables and fruit
	- Tea bags (not the plastic ones)
	- Coffee grounds
- Shredded paper
- Eggshells
- Dryer lint (Not if dryer sheet is used)
- Hair, fur
- Hay, saw, sawdust (can be made from any untreated wood)


### Things that can't be composted
- Citrus (too acidic)
- Meat, oils, grease, animal fats, bones
- Dairy
- Bread
- Onions (release sulfur, harm [[Unsorted/Fungi\|Fungi]] and bacteria)
- Ashes
- Black walnut leaves, twigs
- Diseased infested, or contaminated plants
	- Incl pesticide-treated yard trimmings
- Pet waste
